I'm trying to build a simple notification system in Rust using tokio and I keep getting stuck on how to handle asynchronous requests properly. Here is my draft code where I define an actor struct that holds a channel, but I think I'm misunderstanding the ownership rules here.

```
struct NotificationActor {
    inbox: mpsc::Receiver<Notification>,
}

impl NotificationActor {
    async fn run(&mut self) -> Result<(), Error> {
        while let Some(msg) = self.inbox.recv().await {
            match msg {
                Command::Start => { /* do something */ },
                Command::Stop => break,
                Command::Ask(who, reply) => {
                    // I think the answer is in here?
                    tokio::spawn(async move { who.reply(reply).await? });
                }
            }
        }
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

I assumed that `reply` could be moved into the spawn block like this, but it fails to compile. I thought the actor would just hold a reference and let tokio handle the rest.
